                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>however as congregations are now con-<lb/>stituted I regret to say too much\n                dif-<lb/>ference of feeling exists, &amp; too much dis-<lb/>satisfaction prevails,\n                Alas! For the poor<lb/> Hazanim, our lot is not always cast<lb/> in pleasant places,\n                although we must<lb/> not murmur, I should like to have<lb/> been made aware of the\n                mode of living<lb/> domestic expenses &amp;c, so as to form an<lb/> estimate of\n                situation <hi rend=\"underline\">&amp; place</hi>; but for<lb/> that I of course have\n                to thank myself<lb/> for not seeking your advice in time.<lb/> I may yet not be too\n                late, could you<lb/> respond to this promptly, I am happy<lb/> to hear my old friend\n                    <persName>Revd S. Jacobs</persName> is<lb/> officiating in your city, and I\n                trust<lb/> he may continue long in his occu-<lb/>pation to render the congregation\n                the<lb/> benefit of his valuable services.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\"><persName>Mr. Nathan</persName> in his commu-<lb/>nication to you in\n                my behalf, more<lb/> or less represented to you my position<lb/> in the present\n                sphere of my labors,<lb/> and gave you a faithful account<lb/> of the nature of the\n                difficulties under<lb/> which I am now laboring, and I<lb/> feel within myself that\n                nothing but<lb/> a fair field for the <sic>developement</sic> of<lb/> my\n                energies—which I am impressed</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3sb3xk0h/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
